parts.text:
```json
{
"application": "Spack",
"software": [
"Ghostscript 9.54.0",
"gcc 10.2.0",
"meson 0.60.0",
"ninja 1.10.2",
"py-setuptools 58.2.0",
"python 3.8.12",
"bzip2 1.0.8",
"expat 2.4.1",
"libbsd 0.11.3",
"libmd 1.0.3",
"gdbm 1.21",
"readline 8.1",
"ncurses 6.2",
"gettext 0.21",
"libiconv 1.16",
"libxml2 2.9.12",
"xz 5.2.5",
"zlib 1.2.11",
"tar 1.34",
"libffi 3.3",
"openssl 1.1.1k",
"sqlite 3.36.0",
"util-linux-uuid 2.36.2",
"librsvg 2.42.7"
],
"resource": {
"scheduler": "SLURM",
"reservation": "rocky8u7_testing",
"account": "use300",
"partition": "compute",
"nodes": 1,
"tasks": 1,
"cpus": 16,
"memory": "242G",
"time": "04:00:00",
"scratch": "/scratch/${USER}/job_${SLURM_JOB_ID}"
}
}
```

This script uses Spack, a package manager for high-performance computing, to install Ghostscript 9.54.0 with specific dependencies and configurations. It runs on a SLURM cluster, utilizing resources like a dedicated node with 16 CPUs and 242GB of memory. The script also leverages Spack's configuration settings and handles dependency resolution and installation.
